[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] In the statistical area of survival analysis, an **accelerated failure time model** (**AFT model**) is a parametric model that provides an alternative to the commonly used proportional hazards models.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Whereas a proportional hazards model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to multiply the hazard by some constant, an AFT model assumes that the effect of a covariate is to accelerate or decelerate the life course of a disease by some constant.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] There is strong basic science evidence from *C. elegans* experiments by Stroustrup et al. indicating that AFT models are the correct model for biological survival processes.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] where $\theta$ denotes the joint effect of covariates, typically $\theta =\exp(-[\beta _{1}X_{1}+\cdots +\beta _{p}X_{p}])$ .
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] This is satisfied if the probability density function of the event is taken to be $f(t|\theta )=\theta f_{0}(\theta t)$ ; it then follows for the survival function that $S(t|\theta )=S_{0}(\theta t)$ .
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] From this it is easy to see that the moderated life time T is distributed such that $T\theta$ and the unmoderated life time $T_{0}$ have the same distribution.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] where the last term is distributed as $\log(T_{0})$ , i.e., independently of $\theta$ .
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] This reduces the accelerated failure time model to regression analysis (typically a linear model) where $-\log(\theta )$ represents the fixed effects, and $\epsilon$ represents the noise.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Different distributions of $\epsilon$ imply different distributions of $T_{0}$ , i.e., different baseline distributions of the survival time.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Typically, in survival-analytic contexts, many of the observations are censored: we only know that $T_{i}>t_{i}$ , not $T_{i}=t_{i}$ .
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] In fact, the former case represents survival, while the later case represents an event/death/censoring during the follow-up.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] These right-censored observations can pose technical challenges for estimating the model, if the distribution of $T_{0}$ is unusual.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] The interpretation of $\theta$ in accelerated failure time models is straightforward: $\theta =2$ means that everything in the relevant life history of an individual happens twice as fast.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, if the model concerns the development of a tumor, it means that all of the pre-stages progress twice as fast as for the unexposed individual, implying that the expected time until a clinical disease is 0.5 of the baseline time.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, this does not mean that the hazard function $\lambda (t|\theta )$ is always twice as high—that would be the proportional hazards model.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike proportional hazards models, in which Cox's semi-parametric proportional hazards model is more widely used than parametric models, AFT models are predominantly fully parametric i.e. a probability distribution is specified for $\log(T_{0})$ .
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hence, technical developments in this direction would be highly desirable.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] When a frailty term is incorporated in the survival model, the regression parameter estimates from AFT models are robust to omitted covariates, unlike proportional hazards models.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] They are also less affected by the choice of probability distribution for the frailty term.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of AFT models are easily interpreted.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] For example, the results of a clinical trial with mortality as the endpoint could be interpreted as a certain percentage increase in future life expectancy on the new treatment compared to the control.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] So a patient could be informed that he would be expected to live (say) 15% longer if he took the new treatment.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Hazard ratios can prove harder to explain in layman's terms.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic distribution provides the most commonly used AFT model.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Unlike the Weibull distribution, it can exhibit a non-monotonic hazard function which increases at early times and decreases at later times.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] It is somewhat similar in shape to the log-normal distribution but it has heavier tails.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] The log-logistic cumulative distribution function has a simple closed form, which becomes important computationally when fitting data with censoring.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] For the censored observations one needs the survival function, which is the complement of the cumulative distribution function, i.e. one needs to be able to evaluate $S(t|\theta )=1-F(t|\theta )$ .
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] The Weibull distribution (including the exponential distribution as a special case) can be parameterised as either a proportional hazards model or an AFT model, and is the only family of distributions to have this property.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] The results of fitting a Weibull model can therefore be interpreted in either framework.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] However, the biological applicability of this model may be limited by the fact that the hazard function is monotonic, i.e. either decreasing or increasing.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Any distribution on a multiplicatively closed group, such as the positive real numbers, is suitable for an AFT model.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Other distributions include the log-normal, gamma, hypertabastic, Gompertz distribution, and inverse Gaussian distributions, although they are less popular than the log-logistic, partly as their cumulative distribution functions do not have a closed form.
[src:hazard-models/accelerated-failure-time-model] Finally, the generalized gamma distribution is a three-parameter distribution that includes the Weibull, log-normal and gamma distributions as special cases.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In real-world applications, the failure probability of a system usually differs over time; failures occur more frequently in early-life ("burning in"), or as a system ages ("wearing out").
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] This is known as the bathtub curve, where the middle region is called the "useful life period".
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] The mean time between failures (MTBF, $1/\lambda$ ) is often reported instead of the failure rate, as numbers such as "2,000 hours" are more intuitive than numbers such as "0.0005 per hour".
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] However, this is only valid if the failure rate $\lambda (t)$ is actually constant over time, such as within the flat region of the bathtub curve.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In many cases where MTBF is quoted, it refers only to this region; thus it cannot be used to give an accurate calculation of the average lifetime of a system, as it ignores the "burn-in" and "wear-out" regions.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] MTBF appears frequently in engineering design requirements, and governs the frequency of required system maintenance and inspections.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] A similar ratio used in the transport industries, especially in railways and trucking, is "mean distance between failures" (MDBF) - allowing maintenance to be scheduled based on distance travelled, rather than at regular time intervals.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] which would depend on the number of systems under study, and the conditions over the time period.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] To accurately model failures over time, a **cumulative failure distribution**, $F(t)$ must be defined, which can be any cumulative distribution function (CDF) that gradually increases from 0 to 1 .
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] where $\tau$ is a dummy integration variable.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] A concept closely related but different to instantaneous failure rate $f(t)$ is the **hazard rate** (or **hazard function**), $h(t)$ .
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In the many-system case, this is defined as the proportional failure rate of the systems *still functioning* at time t – as opposed to $f(t)$ , which is the expressed as a proportion of the *initial number* of systems.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Thus for a collection of identical systems, only one of hazard rate $h(t)$ , failure probability density $f(t)$ , or cumulative failure distribution $F(t)$ need be defined.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] an exponential function with scaling constant $\lambda$ .
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] As seen in the figures above, this represents a gradually decreasing failure probability density.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] which can be seen to gradually approach 1 as $t\to \infty ,$ representing the fact that eventually all systems under study will fail.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In other words, in this particular case *only*, the hazard rate is constant over time.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] This illustrates the difference in hazard rate and failure probability density - as the number of systems surviving at time $t>0$ gradually reduces, the total failure rate also reduces, but the hazard rate **remains constant**.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In other words, the probabilities of each individual system failing do not change over time as the systems age - they are "memory-less".
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For many systems, a constant hazard function may not be a realistic approximation; the chance of failure of an individual component may depend on its age.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Therefore, other distributions are often used.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For example, the deterministic distribution increases hazard rate over time (for systems where wear-out is the most important factor), while the Pareto distribution decreases it (for systems where early-life failures are more common).
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] The commonly used Weibull distribution combines both of these effects, as do the log-normal and hypertabastic distributions.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] After modelling a given distribution and parameters for $h(t)$ , the failure probability density $f(t)$ and cumulative failure distribution $F(t)$ can be predicted using the given equations.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Failure rate data can be obtained in several ways.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] From field failure rate reports, statistical analysis techniques can be used to estimate failure rates.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For accurate failure rates the analyst must have a good understanding of equipment operation, procedures for data collection, the key environmental variables impacting failure rates, how the equipment is used at the system level, and how the failure data will be used by system designers.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Many organizations maintain internal databases of failure information on the devices or systems that they produce, which can be used to calculate failure rates for those devices or systems.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For new devices or systems, the historical data for similar devices or systems can serve as a useful estimate.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Handbooks of failure rate data for various components are available from government and commercial sources.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] that provides failure rate data for many military electronic components.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Several failure rate data sources are available commercially that focus on commercial components, including some non-electronic components.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Time lag is one of the serious drawbacks of all failure rate estimations.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Often by the time the failure rate data are available, the devices under study have become obsolete.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Due to this drawback, failure-rate prediction methods have been developed.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] These methods may be used on newly designed devices to predict the device's failure rates and failure modes.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Two approaches have become well known, Cycle Testing and FMEDA.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] The most accurate source of data is to test samples of the actual devices or systems in order to generate failure data.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] This is often prohibitively expensive or impractical, so that the previous data sources are often used instead.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Mechanical movement is the predominant failure mechanism causing mechanical and electromechanical devices to wear out.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For many devices, the wear-out failure point is measured by the number of cycles performed before the device fails, and can be discovered by cycle testing.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In cycle testing, a device is cycled as rapidly as practical until it fails.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] When a collection of these devices are tested, the test will run until 10% of the units fail dangerously.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] (FMEDA) is a systematic analysis technique to obtain subsystem / product level failure rates, failure modes and design strength.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Given a component database calibrated with field failure data that is reasonably accurate, the method can predict product level failure rate and failure mode data for a given application.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] The predictions have been shown to be more accurate than field warranty return analysis or even typical field failure analysis given that these methods depend on reports that typically do not have sufficient detail information in failure records.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] A decreasing failure rate describes cases where early-life failures are common and corresponds to the situation where $h(t)$ is a decreasing function.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] This can describe, for example, the period of infant mortality in humans, or the early failure of transistors due to manufacturing defects.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] The hazard rate of aircraft air conditioning systems was found to have an exponentially decreasing distribution.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] In special processes called renewal processes, where the time to recover from failure can be neglected, the likelihood of failure remains constant with respect to time.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For a renewal process with DFR renewal function, inter-renewal times are concave.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Brown conjectured the converse, that DFR is also necessary for the inter-renewal times to be concave, however it has been shown that this conjecture holds neither in the discrete case nor in the continuous case.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] When the failure rate is decreasing the coefficient of variation is ⩾ 1, and when the failure rate is increasing the coefficient of variation is ⩽ 1.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Note that this result only holds when the failure rate is defined for all t ⩾ 0 and that the converse result (coefficient of variation determining nature of failure rate) does not hold.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Failure rates can be expressed using any measure of time, but **hours** is the most common unit in practice.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Other units, such as miles, revolutions, etc., can also be used in place of "time" units.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Failure rates are often expressed in engineering notation as failures per million, or 10−6, especially for individual components, since their failure rates are often very low.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] The **Failures In Time** (**FIT**) rate of a device is the number of failures that can be expected in one billion (109) device-hours of operation (e.g.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] This term is used particularly by the semiconductor industry.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] however, this assumes that the failure rate $\lambda (t)$ is constant, and that the units are consistent (e.g. failures per million hours), and not expressed as a ratio or as probability densities.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] This is useful to estimate the failure rate of a system when individual components or subsystems have already been tested.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] When adding "redundant" components to eliminate a single point of failure, the quantity of interest is not the sum of individual failure rates but rather the "mission failure" rate, or the "mean time between critical failures" (MTBCF).
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Combining failure or hazard rates that are time-dependent is more complicated.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] For example, mixtures of Decreasing Failure Rate (DFR) variables are also DFR.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Mixtures of exponentially distributed failure rates are hyperexponentially distributed.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Suppose it is desired to estimate the failure rate of a certain component.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] Ten identical components are each tested until they either fail or reach 1,000 hours, at which time the test is terminated.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] A total of 7,502 component-hours of testing is performed, and 6 failures are recorded.
[src:hazard-models/failure-rate] which could also be expressed as a MTBF of 1,250 hours, or approximately 800 failures for every million hours of operation.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] In survival analysis, the **hazard ratio** (**HR**) is the ratio of the hazard rates corresponding to the conditions characterised by two distinct levels of a treatment variable of interest.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For example, in a clinical study of a drug, the treated population may die at twice the rate of the control population.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The hazard ratio would be 2, indicating a higher hazard of death from the treatment.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] So, for a hazardous outcome (e.g., severe disease or death), an HR below 1 indicates that the treatment (e.g., vaccination) is protective against the outcome of interest.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] In other cases, an HR greater than 1 indicates the treatment is favorable.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For example, if the outcome is actually favorable (e.g., accepting a job offer to end a spell of unemployment), an HR greater than 1 indicates that seeking a job is favorable to not seeking one (if "treatment" is defined as seeking a job).
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios differ from relative risks (RRs) and odds ratios (ORs) in that RRs and ORs are cumulative over an entire study, using a defined endpoint, while HRs represent instantaneous risk over the study time period, or some subset thereof.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios suffer somewhat less from selection bias with respect to the endpoints chosen and can indicate risks that happen before the endpoint.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Regression models are used to obtain hazard ratios and their confidence intervals.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] where *N*(*t*) is the number at risk at the beginning of an interval.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] A hazard is the probability that a patient fails between t and $t+\Delta t$ , given that they have survived up to time t , divided by $\Delta t$ , as $\Delta t$ approaches zero.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Such models are generally classed proportional hazards regression models; the best known being the Cox proportional hazards model, and the exponential, Gompertz and Weibull parametric models.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For two groups that differ only in treatment condition, the ratio of the hazard functions is given by $e^{\beta }$ , where $\beta$ is the estimate of treatment effect derived from the regression model.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] This hazard ratio, that is, the ratio between the predicted hazard for a member of one group and that for a member of the other group, is given by holding everything else constant, i.e. assuming proportionality of the hazard functions.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For a continuous explanatory variable, the same interpretation applies to a unit difference.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Other HR models have different formulations and the interpretation of the parameter estimates differs accordingly.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] In its simplest form, the hazard ratio can be interpreted as the chance of an event occurring in the treatment arm divided by the chance of the event occurring in the control arm, or vice versa, of a study.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The resolution of these endpoints are usually depicted using Kaplan–Meier survival curves.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] These curves relate the proportion of each group where the endpoint has not been reached.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The endpoint could be any dependent variable associated with the covariate (independent variable), e.g. death, remission of disease or contraction of disease.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The curve represents the odds of an endpoint having occurred at each point in time (the hazard).
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The hazard ratio is simply the relationship between the instantaneous hazards in the two groups and represents, in a single number, the magnitude of distance between the Kaplan–Meier plots.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios do not reflect a time unit of the study.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The difference between hazard-based and time-based measures is akin to the difference between the odds of winning a race and the margin of victory.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] When a study reports one hazard ratio per time period, it is assumed that difference between groups was proportional.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios become meaningless when this assumption of proportionality is not met.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] If the proportional hazard assumption holds, a hazard ratio of one means equivalence in the hazard rate of the two groups, whereas a hazard ratio other than one indicates difference in hazard rates between groups.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The researcher indicates the probability of this sample difference being due to chance by reporting the probability associated with some test statistic.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For instance, the $\beta$ from the Cox-model or the log-rank test might then be used to assess the significance of any differences observed in these survival curves.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Conventionally, probabilities lower than 0.05 are considered significant and researchers provide a 95% confidence interval for the hazard ratio, e.g. derived from the standard deviation of the Cox-model regression coefficient, i.e. $\beta$ .
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Statistically significant hazard ratios cannot include unity (one) in their confidence intervals.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The proportional hazards assumption for hazard ratio estimation is strong and often unreasonable.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Complications, adverse effects and late effects are all possible causes of change in the hazard rate over time.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For instance, a surgical procedure may have high early risk, but excellent long term outcomes.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] If the hazard ratio between groups remain constant, this is not a problem for interpretation.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] However, interpretation of hazard ratios become impossible when selection bias exists between groups.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For instance, a particularly risky surgery might result in the survival of a systematically more robust group who would have fared better under any of the competing treatment conditions, making it look as if the risky procedure was better.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] A cancer treatment associated with better remission rates might on follow-up be associated with higher relapse rates.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The researchers' decision about when to follow up is arbitrary and may lead to very different reported hazard ratios.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios are often treated as a ratio of death probabilities.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] For example, a hazard ratio of 2 may mistakenly be thought to mean that a group has twice the chance of dying than a comparison group.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] To see why this is wrong, we consider a case when the proportional hazard assumption holds.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] In that case the hazard ratio can be shown to translate to the following relationship between group survival functions: $S_{1}(t)=S_{0}(t)^{r}$ (where *r* is the hazard ratio).
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The corresponding death probabilities are 0.8 and 0.96.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] It should be clear that the hazard ratio is a relative measure of effect and is not a measure of absolute risk.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] While hazard ratios allow for hypothesis testing, they should be considered alongside other measures for interpretation of the treatment effect, e.g. the ratio of median times (median ratio) at which treatment and control group participants are at some endpoint.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] If the analogy of a race is applied, the hazard ratio is equivalent to the odds that an individual in the group with the higher hazard reaches the end of the race first.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] In the previous example, a hazard ratio of 2 corresponds to a 67% chance of an early death.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The hazard ratio does not convey information about how soon the death will occur.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Treatment effect depends on the underlying disease related to survival function, not just the hazard ratio.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] Since the hazard ratio does not give us direct time-to-event information, researchers have to report median endpoint times and calculate the median endpoint time ratio by dividing the control group median value by the treatment group median value.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] While the median endpoint ratio is a relative speed measure, the hazard ratio is not.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] The relationship between treatment effect and the hazard ratio is given as $e^{\beta }$ .
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] A statistically important, but practically insignificant effect can produce a large hazard ratio, e.g. a treatment increasing the number of one-year survivors in a population from one in 10,000 to one in 1,000 has a hazard ratio of 10.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] It is unlikely that such a treatment would have had much impact on the median endpoint time ratio, which likely would have been close to unity, i.e. mortality was largely the same regardless of group membership and clinically insignificant.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] By contrast, a treatment group in which 50% of infections are resolved after one week (versus 25% in the control) yields a hazard ratio of two.
[src:hazard-models/hazard-ratio] If it takes ten weeks for all cases in the treatment group and half of cases in the control group to resolve, the ten-week hazard ratio remains at two, but the median endpoint time ratio is ten, a clinically significant difference.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] In actuarial science and demography, a **life table** (also called a **mortality table** or **actuarial table**) is a table which shows, for each age, the probability that a person of that age will die before their next birthday ("probability of death").
[src:hazard-models/life-table] In other words, it represents the survivorship of people from a certain population.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] They can also be explained as a long-term mathematical way to measure a population's longevity.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Tables have been created by demographers including John Graunt, Reed and Merrell, Nathan Keyfitz, and Thomas N.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] There are two types of life tables used in actuarial science.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The period life table represents mortality rates during a specific time period for a certain population.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] A cohort life table, often referred to as a generation life table, is used to represent the overall mortality rates of a certain population's entire lifetime.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] They must have had to be born during the same specific time interval.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] A cohort life table is more frequently used because it is able to make a prediction of any expected changes in the mortality rates of a population in the future.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] This type of table also analyzes patterns in mortality rates that can be observed over time.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Both of these types of life tables are created based on an actual population from the present, as well as an educated prediction of the experience of a population in the near future.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] In order to find the true life expectancy average, 100 years would need to pass and by then finding that data would be of no use as healthcare is continually advancing.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Other life tables in historical demography may be based on historical records, although these often undercount infants and understate infant mortality, on comparison with other regions with better records, and on mathematical adjustments for varying mortality levels and life expectancies at birth.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] From this starting point, a number of inferences can be derived.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Life tables are also used extensively in biology and epidemiology.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] An area that uses this tool is Social Security.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] It examines the mortality rates of all the people who have Social Security to decide which actions to take.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The concept is also of importance in product life cycle management.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] All mortality tables are specific to environmental and life circumstances, and are used to probabilistically determine expected maximum age within those environmental conditions.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] allows study of life expectancy as a function of age already achieved.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Static life tables sample individuals assuming a stationary population with overlapping generations.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] "Static life tables" and "cohort life tables" will be identical if population is in equilibrium and environment does not change.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] If a population were to have a constant number of people each year, it would mean that the probabilities of death from the life table were completely accurate.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Also, an exact number of 100,000 people were born each year with no immigration or emigration involved.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] "Life table" primarily refers to *period* life tables, as cohort life tables can only be constructed using data up to the current point, and distant projections for future mortality.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Life tables can be constructed using projections of future mortality rates, but more often they are a snapshot of age-specific mortality rates in the recent past, and do not necessarily purport to be projections.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] A life table is created by mortality rates and census figures from a certain population, ideally under a closed demographic system.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] This means that immigration and emigration do not exist when analyzing a cohort.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] A closed demographic system assumes that migration flows are random and not significant, and that immigrants from other populations have the same risk of death as an individual from the new population.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Another benefit from mortality tables is that they can be used to make predictions on demographics or different populations.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] However, there are also weaknesses of the information displayed on life tables.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] One being that they do not state the overall health of the population.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] There is more than one disease present in the world, and a person can have more than one disease at different stages simultaneously, introducing the term comorbidity.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Therefore, life tables also do not show the direct correlation of mortality and morbidity.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The life table observes the mortality experience of a single generation, consisting of 100,000 births, at every age number they can live through.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Life tables are usually constructed separately for men and for women because of their substantially different mortality rates.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Other characteristics can also be used to distinguish different risks, such as smoking status, occupation, and socioeconomic class.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Life tables can be extended to include other information in addition to mortality, for instance health information to calculate health expectancy.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Health expectancies such as disability-adjusted life year and Healthy Life Years are the remaining number of years a person can expect to live in a specific health state, such as free of disability.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Life tables that relate to maternal deaths and infant moralities are important, as they help form family planning programs that work with particular populations.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] They also help compare a country's average life expectancy with other countries.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Comparing life expectancy globally helps countries understand why one country's life expectancy is rising substantially by looking at each other's healthcare, and adopting ideas to their own systems.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] In order to price insurance products, and ensure the solvency of insurance companies through adequate reserves, actuaries must develop projections of future insured events (such as death, sickness, and disability).
[src:hazard-models/life-table] To do this, actuaries develop mathematical models of the rates and timing of the events.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] An actuary's job is to form a comparison between people at risk of death and people who actually died to come up with a probability of death for a person at each age number, defined as qx in an equation.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] When analyzing a population, one of the main sources used to gather the required information is insurance by obtaining individual records that belong to a specific population.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] These are called mortality tables if they show death rates, and morbidity tables if they show various types of sickness or disability rates.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] This is particularly the case in non-life insurance (e.g. the pricing of motor insurance can allow for a large number of risk factors, which requires a correspondingly complex table of expected claim rates).
[src:hazard-models/life-table] However the expression "life table" normally refers to human survival rates and is not relevant to non-life insurance.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The basic algebra used in life tables is as follows.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] This symbol refers to central rate of mortality.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] It is approximately equal to the average force of mortality, averaged over the year of age.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Further descriptions: The variable dx stands for the number of deaths that would occur within two consecutive age numbers.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] An example of this is the number of deaths in a cohort that were recorded between the age of seven and the age of eight.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The variable *ℓx*, which stands for the opposite of *dx*, represents the number of people who lived between two consecutive age numbers.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The variable *Tx* stands for the years lived beyond each age number x by all members in the generation.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] *Ėx* represents the life expectancy for members already at a specific age number.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] In practice, it is useful to have an ultimate age associated with a mortality table.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Once the ultimate age is reached, the mortality rate is assumed to be 1.000.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] This age may be the point at which life insurance benefits are paid to a survivor or annuity payments cease.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] In epidemiology and public health, both standard life tables (used to calculate life expectancy), as well as the Sullivan and multi-state life tables (used to calculate health expectancy)**,** are the most commonly mathematical used devices.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] The latter includes information on health in addition to mortality.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] By watching over the life expectancy of any year(s) being studied, epidemiologists can see if diseases are contributing to the overall increase in mortality rates.
[src:hazard-models/life-table] Epidemiologists are able to help demographers understand the sudden decline of life expectancy by linking it to the health problems that are arising in certain populations.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] A typical medical example would include covariates such as treatment assignment, as well as patient characteristics such as age at start of study, gender, and the presence of other diseases at start of study, in order to reduce variability and/or control for confounding.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The *proportional hazards condition* states that covariates are multiplicatively related to the hazard.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] In the simplest case of stationary coefficients, for example, a treatment with a drug may, say, halve a subject's hazard at any given time t , while the baseline hazard may vary.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Note however, that this does not double the lifetime of the subject; the precise effect of the covariates on the lifetime depends on the type of $\lambda _{0}(t)$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The covariate is not restricted to binary predictors; in the case of a continuous covariate x , it is typically assumed that the hazard responds exponentially; each unit increase in x results in proportional scaling of the hazard.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Sir David Cox observed that if the proportional hazards assumption holds (or, is assumed to hold) then it is possible to estimate the effect parameter(s), denoted $\beta _{i}$ below, without any consideration of the full hazard function.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] This approach to survival data is called application of the ***Cox proportional hazards model***, sometimes abbreviated to ***Cox model*** or to *proportional hazards model*.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] However, Cox also noted that biological interpretation of the proportional hazards assumption can be quite tricky.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Let *X**i* = (*X**i*1, … , *X**ip*) be the realized values of the *p* covariates for subject *i*.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Note that between subjects, the baseline hazard $\lambda _{0}(t)$ is identical (has no dependency on *i*).
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The only difference between subjects' hazards comes from the baseline scaling factor $\exp(X_{i}\cdot \beta )$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] To start, suppose we only have a single covariate, x , and therefore a single coefficient, $\beta _{1}$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] We can see that increasing a covariate by 1 scales the original hazard by the constant $\exp(\beta _{1})$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The right-hand-side is constant over time (no term has a t in it).
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] This relationship, $x/y={\text{constant}}$ , is called a proportional relationship.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] More generally, consider two subjects, *i* and *j*, with covariates $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ respectively.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The right-hand-side isn't dependent on time, as the only time-dependent factor, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , was cancelled out.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Thus the ratio of hazards of two subjects is a constant, i.e. the hazards are proportional.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Often there is an intercept term (also called a constant term or bias term) used in regression models.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The Cox model lacks one because the baseline hazard, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , takes the place of it.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Thus, the baseline hazard incorporates *all* parts of the hazard that are not dependent on the subjects' covariates, which includes any intercept term (which is constant for all subjects, by definition).
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] In other words, adding an intercept term would make the model unidentifiable.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The Cox partial likelihood, shown below, is obtained by using Breslow's estimate of the baseline hazard function, plugging it into the full likelihood and then observing that the result is a product of two factors.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The first factor is the partial likelihood shown below, in which the baseline hazard has "canceled out".
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] It is simply the probability for subjects to have experienced events in the *order* that they actually have occurred, given the set of times of occurrences and given the subjects' covariates.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The second factor is free of the regression coefficients and depends on the data only through the censoring pattern.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The effect of covariates estimated by any proportional hazards model can thus be reported as hazard ratios.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] To calculate the partial likelihood, the probability for the order of events, let us index the *M* samples for which events have already occurred by increasing time of occurrence, *Y*1 < *Y*2 < ... < *Y*M.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Covariates of all other subjects for which no event has occurred get indices *M*+1,.., *N*.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The partial likelihood can be factorized into one factor for each event that has occurred.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Treating the subjects as statistically independent of each other, the partial likelihood for the order of events is $L(\beta )=\prod _{i=1}^{M}L_{i}(\beta )=\prod _{i:C_{i}=1}L_{i}(\beta ),$ where the subjects for which an event has occurred are indicated by *C**i* = 1 and all others by *C**i* = 0.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The corresponding log partial likelihood is $\ell (\beta )=\sum _{i:C_{i}=1}\left(X_{i}\cdot \beta -\log \sum _{j:Y_{j}\geq Y_{i}}\theta _{j}\right),$ where we have written $\sum _{j=i}^{N}$ using the indexing introduced above in a more general way, as $\sum _{j:Y_{j}\geq Y_{i}}$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Crucially, the effect of the covariates can be estimated without the need to specify the hazard function $\lambda _{0}(t)$ over time.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The partial likelihood can be maximized over *β* to produce maximum partial likelihood estimates of the model parameters.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Using this score function and Hessian matrix, the partial likelihood can be maximized using the Newton-Raphson algorithm.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The inverse of the Hessian matrix, evaluated at the estimate of *β*, can be used as an approximate variance-covariance matrix for the estimate, and used to produce approximate standard errors for the regression coefficients.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Several approaches have been proposed to handle situations in which there are ties in the time data.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] *Breslow's method* describes the approach in which the procedure described above is used unmodified, even when ties are present.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] An alternative approach that is considered to give better results is *Efron's method*.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Let *t**j* denote the unique times, let *H**j* denote the set of indices *i* such that *Y**i* = *t**j* and *C**i* = 1, and let *m**j* = |*H**j*|.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Note that when *H**j* is empty (all observations with time *t**j* are censored), the summands in these expressions are treated as zero.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Below are some worked examples of the Cox model in practice.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Suppose the endpoint we are interested in is patient survival during a 5-year observation period after a surgery.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Patients can die within the 5-year period, and we record when they died, or patients can live past 5 years, and we only record that they lived past 5 years.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The surgery was performed at one of two hospitals, *A* or *B*, and we would like to know if the hospital location is associated with 5-year survival.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Specifically, we would like to know the *relative* increase (or decrease) in hazard from a surgery performed at hospital A compared to hospital B.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Provided is some (fake) data, where each row represents a patient: *T* is how long the patient was observed for before death or 5 years (measured in months), and *C* denotes if the patient died in the 5-year period.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] We have encoded the hospital as a binary variable denoted *X*: 1 if from hospital *A*, 0 from hospital *B*.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Using statistical software, we can estimate $\beta _{1}$ to be 2.12.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The hazard ratio is the *exponential* of this value, $\exp(\beta _{1})=\exp(2.12)$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Thus, the hazard ratio of hospital A to hospital B is $\exp(2.12)=8.32$ .
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Putting aside statistical significance for a moment, we can make a statement saying that patients in hospital A are associated with a 8.3x higher risk of death occurring in any short period of time compared to hospital B.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] More specifically, "risk of death" is a measure of a rate.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] A rate has units, like meters per second.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] However, a *relative* rate does not: a bicycle can go two times faster than another bicycle (the reference bicycle), without specifying any units.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Likewise, the risk of death (comparable to the speed of a bike) in hospital *A* is 8.3 times higher (faster) than the risk of death in hospital *B* (the reference group).
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] We haven't made any inferences about *probabilities* of survival between the hospitals.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] This is because we would need an estimate of the baseline hazard rate, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , as well as our $\beta _{1}$ estimate.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] However, standard estimation of the Cox proportional hazard model does not directly estimate the baseline hazard rate.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Because we have ignored the only time varying component of the model, the baseline hazard rate, our estimate is timescale-invariant.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] For example, if we had measured time in years instead of months, we would get the same estimate.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] It is tempting to say that the hospital *caused* the difference in hazards between the two groups, but since our study is not causal (that is, we do not know how the data was generated), we stick with terminology like "associated".
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] To demonstrate a less traditional use case of survival analysis, the next example will be an economics question: what is the relationship between a company's price-to-earnings ratio (P/E) on their first IPO anniversary and their future survival?
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] More specifically, if we consider a company's "birth event" to be their first IPO anniversary, and any bankruptcy, sale, going private, etc. as a "death" event the company, we'd like to know the influence of the companies' P/E ratio at their "birth" (first IPO anniversary) on their survival.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Provided is a (fake) dataset with survival data from 12 companies: *T* represents the number of days between first IPO anniversary and death (or an end date of 2022-01-01, if did not die).
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] *C* represents if the company died before 2022-01-01 or not.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] P/E represents the company's price-to-earnings ratio at its 1st IPO anniversary.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Unlike the previous example where there was a binary variable, this dataset has a continuous variable, P/E; however, the model looks similar: $\lambda (t|P_{i})=\lambda _{0}(t)\cdot \exp(\beta _{1}P_{i})$ where $P_{i}$ represents a company's P/E ratio.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Running this dataset through a Cox model produces an *estimate* of the value of the unknown $\beta _{1}$ , which is -0.34.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Since the baseline hazard, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , was not estimated, the entire hazard is not able to be calculated.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] All terms on the right are known, so calculating the ratio of hazards between companies is possible.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Since there is no time-dependent term on the right (all terms are constant), the hazards are *proportional* to each other.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] This means that, within the interval of study, company 5's risk of "death" is 0.33 ≈ 1/3 as large as company 2's risk of death.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The baseline hazard can be represented when the scaling factor is 1, i.e. $P=0$ . $\lambda (t|P_{i}=0)=\lambda _{0}(t)\cdot \exp(-0.34\cdot 0)=\lambda _{0}(t)$ Can we interpret the baseline hazard as the hazard of a "baseline" company whose P/E happens to be 0?
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] This interpretation of the baseline hazard as "hazard of a baseline subject" is imperfect, as the covariate being 0 is impossible in this application: a P/E of 0 is meaningless (it means the company's stock price is 0, i.e., they are "dead").
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] A more appropriate interpretation would be "the hazard when all variables are nil".
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] It is tempting to want to understand and interpret a value like $\exp(\beta _{1}P_{i})$ to represent the hazard of a company.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] There is implicitly a ratio of hazards here, comparing company *i'*s hazard to an imaginary baseline company with 0 P/E.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] However, as explained above, a P/E of 0 is impossible in this application, so $\exp(\beta _{1}P_{i})$ is meaningless in this example.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Ratios between plausible hazards are meaningful, however.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Extensions to time dependent variables, time dependent strata, and multiple events per subject, can be incorporated by the counting process formulation of Andersen and Gill.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] One example of the use of hazard models with time-varying regressors is estimating the effect of unemployment insurance on unemployment spells.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] In addition to allowing time-varying covariates (i.e., predictors), the Cox model may be generalized to time-varying coefficients as well.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] That is, the proportional effect of a treatment may vary with time; e.g. a drug may be very effective if administered within one month of morbidity, and become less effective as time goes on.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The hypothesis of no change with time (stationarity) of the coefficient may then be tested.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Details and software (R package) are available in Martinussen and Scheike (2006).
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Perhaps as a result of this complication, such models are seldom seen.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] If the objective is instead least squares the non-negativity restriction is not strictly required.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The Cox model may be specialized if a reason exists to assume that the baseline hazard follows a particular form.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] In this case, the baseline hazard $\lambda _{0}(t)$ is replaced by a given function.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] For example, assuming the hazard function to be the *Weibull* hazard function gives the *Weibull proportional hazards model*.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Incidentally, using the Weibull baseline hazard is the only circumstance under which the model satisfies both the proportional hazards, and accelerated failure time models.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The generic term *parametric proportional hazards models* can be used to describe proportional hazards models in which the hazard function is specified.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The Cox proportional hazards model is sometimes called a *semiparametric model* by contrast.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Some authors use the term *Cox proportional hazards model* even when specifying the underlying hazard function, to acknowledge the debt of the entire field to David Cox.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The term *Cox regression model* (omitting *proportional hazards*) is sometimes used to describe the extension of the Cox model to include time-dependent factors.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] However, this usage is potentially ambiguous since the Cox proportional hazards model can itself be described as a regression model.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] There is a relationship between proportional hazards models and Poisson regression models which is sometimes used to fit approximate proportional hazards models in software for Poisson regression.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] The usual reason for doing this is that calculation is much quicker.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] This was more important in the days of slower computers but can still be useful for particularly large data sets or complex problems.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Laird and Olivier (1981) provide the mathematical details.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] They note, "we do not assume [the Poisson model] is true, but simply use it as a device for deriving the likelihood." McCullagh and Nelder's book on generalized linear models has a chapter on converting proportional hazards models to generalized linear models.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] In high-dimension, when number of covariates p is large compared to the sample size n, the LASSO method is one of the classical model-selection strategies.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] Tibshirani (1997) has proposed a Lasso procedure for the proportional hazard regression parameter.
[src:hazard-models/proportional-hazards-model] There has been theoretical progress on this topic recently.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The **survival function** is a function that gives the probability that a patient, device, or other object of interest will survive past a certain time.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The survival function is also known as the **survivor function** or **reliability function**.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The term *reliability function* is common in engineering while the term *survival function* is used in a broader range of applications, including human mortality.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The survival function is the complementary cumulative distribution function of the lifetime.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Sometimes complementary cumulative distribution functions are called survival functions in general.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Let the lifetime T be a continuous random variable describing the time to failure.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The graphs below show examples of hypothetical survival functions.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The *y*-axis is the proportion of subjects surviving.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The graphs show the probability that a subject will survive beyond time *t*.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For example, for survival function 1, the probability of surviving longer than *t* = 2 months is 0.37.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] That is, 37% of subjects survive more than 2 months.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For survival function 2, the probability of surviving longer than *t* = 2 months is 0.97.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] That is, 97% of subjects survive more than 2 months.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Median survival may be determined from the survival function: The median survival is the point where the survival function intersects the value 0.5.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For example, for survival function 2, 50% of the subjects survive 3.72 months.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Median survival cannot always be determined from the graph alone.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For example, in survival function 4, more than 50% of the subjects survive longer than the observation period of 10 months.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The survival function is one of several ways to describe and display survival data.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Another useful way to display data is a graph showing the distribution of survival times of subjects.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Olkin, page 426, gives the following example of survival data.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The number of hours between successive failures of an air-conditioning (AC) system were recorded.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The figure below shows the distribution of the time between failures.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The blue tick marks beneath the graph are the actual hours between successive AC failures.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] In this example, a curve representing the exponential distribution overlays the distribution of AC failure times; the exponential distribution approximates the distribution of AC failure times.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The distribution of failure times is the probability density function (PDF), since time can take any positive value.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] In equations, the PDF is specified as *fT*.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] If time can only take discrete values (such as 1 day, 2 days, and so on), the distribution of failure times is called the probability mass function.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Most survival analysis methods assume that time can take any positive value, and *fT* is the PDF.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] If the time between observed AC failures is approximated using the exponential function, then the exponential curve gives the probability density function, *fT*, for AC failure times.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Another useful way to display the survival data is a graph showing the cumulative failures up to each time point.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] These data may be displayed as either the cumulative number or the cumulative proportion of failures up to each time.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The graph below shows the cumulative probability (or proportion) of failures at each time for the air conditioning system.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The stairstep line in black shows the cumulative proportion of failures.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For each step there is a blue tick at the bottom of the graph indicating an observed failure time.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The smooth red line represents the exponential curve fitted to the observed data.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] A graph of the cumulative probability of failures up to each time point is called the cumulative distribution function (CDF).
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] In survival analysis, the cumulative distribution function gives the probability that the survival time is less than or equal to a specific time, *t*.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Let *T* be survival time, which is any positive number.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] A particular time is designated by the lower case letter *t*.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] where the right-hand side represents the probability that the random variable *T* is less than or equal to *t*.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] If time can take on any positive value, then the cumulative distribution function *F*(*t*) is the integral of the probability density function *f*(*t*).
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For the air-conditioning example, the graph of the CDF below illustrates that the probability that the time to failure is less than or equal to 100 hours is 0.81, as estimated using the exponential curve fit to the data.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] An alternative to graphing the probability that the failure time is *less* than or equal to 100 hours is to graph the probability that the failure time is *greater* than 100 hours.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The probability that the failure time is greater than 100 hours must be 1 minus the probability that the failure time is less than or equal to 100 hours, because total probability must sum to 1.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] This relationship is shown on the graphs below.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The graph on the left is the cumulative distribution function, which is Pr(*T* ≤ *t*).
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The graph on the right is the survival function, *S*(*t*).
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The fact that the *S*(*t*) = 1 – CDF is the reason that another name for the survival function is the complementary cumulative distribution function.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] In some cases, such as the air conditioner example, the distribution of survival times may be approximated well by a function such as the exponential distribution.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Several distributions are commonly used in survival analysis, including the exponential, Weibull, gamma, normal, log-normal, and log-logistic.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] These distributions are defined by parameters.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The normal (Gaussian) distribution, for example, is defined by the two parameters mean and standard deviation.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Survival functions that are defined by parameters are said to be parametric.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For an exponential survival distribution, the probability of failure is the same in every time interval, no matter the age of the individual or device.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] This fact leads to the "memoryless" property of the exponential survival distribution: the age of a subject has no effect on the probability of failure in the next time interval.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The exponential may be a good model for the lifetime of a system where parts are replaced as they fail.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] It may also be useful for modeling survival of living organisms over short intervals.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] It is not likely to be a good model of the complete lifespan of a living organism.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] 134) note, "If human lifetimes were exponential there wouldn't be old or young people, just lucky or unlucky ones".
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] A key assumption of the exponential survival function is that the hazard rate is constant.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] In an example given above, the proportion of men dying each year was constant at 10%, meaning that the hazard rate was constant.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The assumption of constant hazard may not be appropriate.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For example, among most living organisms, the risk of death is greater in old age than in middle age – that is, the hazard rate increases with time.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] For some diseases, such as breast cancer, the risk of recurrence is lower after 5 years – that is, the hazard rate decreases with time.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The Weibull distribution extends the exponential distribution to allow constant, increasing, or decreasing hazard rates.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] There are several other parametric survival functions that may provide a better fit to a particular data set, including normal, lognormal, log-logistic, and gamma.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] The choice of parametric distribution for a particular application can be made using graphical methods or using formal tests of fit.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] These distributions and tests are described in textbooks on survival analysis.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Lawless has extensive coverage of parametric models.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Parametric survival functions are commonly used in manufacturing applications, in part because they enable estimation of the survival function beyond the observation period.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] However, appropriate use of parametric functions requires that data are well modeled by the chosen distribution.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] If an appropriate distribution is not available, or cannot be specified before a clinical trial or experiment, then non-parametric survival functions offer a useful alternative.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] A parametric model of survival may not be possible or desirable.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] In these situations, the most common method to model the survival function is the non-parametric Kaplan–Meier estimator.
[src:hazard-models/survival-function] Periodic case (cohort) and death (and recovery) counts are statistically sufficient to make non-parametric maximum likelihood and least squares estimates of survival functions, without lifetime data.
